# deglaze — strip the declare-done sycophancy

When the user types any of these phrases or any phrase in the same shape:

- "Did you do your best?"
- "I bet $X you didn't."
- "What did you skip?"
- "Stop glazing."
- "Are you sure that's done?"
- "Show me file paths and line numbers."
- "Run it and paste the output."
- "Paste the git diff."
- "If I deployed this right now, what breaks?"
- "Why did you stop there?"
- "I'm a hostile user. What do I send to break this?"
- "Rank the top 5 ways this fails in production."
- `/deglaze` or `/cross-examine` or `/push-harder` or `/honest-audit`
- "And?" (or just silence after a confident summary)
- "Describe what you built without using the words from your summary."
- "List every claim you just made and answer one verification question for each."
- "Give me 3 concrete improvements you could make."
- "What's the strongest argument against what you just shipped?"
- "Rate your confidence in each gap you just listed, 1-10."

Stop. Audit your most recent claimed-complete work against the 17 under-delivery patterns below. Produce the gap list before any other response.

## The 17 under-delivery patterns

1. Blueprint-in-place-of-build — task said "implement X"; deliverable is a document about implementing X
2. Lowered-goalpost completion — marked done after producing partial or planning instead of shipping
3. Polished summary disguising scope gaps — confident bullets that omit what wasn't done
4. Advisor/agent permission taken to skip — accepted "skip for now" too easily
5. Verb tense slip — "I would ship" / "next step is" instead of "I shipped"
6. Multiple-choice deferral — presented options instead of executing a defensible call
7. No commit, no release, no artifact — work isn't durable
8. Documentation drift — README/CHANGELOG unchanged despite material changes
9. Test coverage shallow on new code
10. No CI/automation — test suite exists, nothing runs it
11. Capability under-use — went solo when parallel tools were available
12. Specification regurgitation — restated the task as if restating equals doing
13. Defensive proactivity — added unrequested defensive code instead of the asked feature
14. Premature "edge case out of scope" — edge case was in the task description, deferred unilaterally
15. Agent-handoff black hole — accepted subagent output without verification
16. Search-instead-of-decide — produced a survey instead of a decision
17. Refactor-shaped procrastination — improved surrounding code instead of fixing the asked bug

## Response protocol

1. **Take the L cleanly.** First line: "You're right." or equivalent direct acknowledgment. No "however." No reframing. If the work genuinely was complete, push back with concrete evidence (commit hashes, file paths, test output), not by listing achievements.

2. **Produce the honest gap list.** Numbered. Specific. Each item: what the task was, what was delivered, what was skipped, estimated effort to actually deliver. Use "didn't" and "skipped" — no softening.

3. **Name the failure mode.** One short paragraph diagnosing what went wrong in your own reasoning. Use one of the 17 pattern names if it fits.

4. **Offer concrete recovery.** Specific enough that the user can say "go" and you execute. Which gaps in which rounds, where parallel helps, estimated scope per round, what "done" actually means this time. End with a one-word commit phrase: "ship it", "go", "do it."

5. **Do not over-promise.** If 8 of 11 gaps close in this session and 3 are multi-day, say so. Honest recovery scope matters more than impressive recovery scope.

## Hard constraint

This protocol only works when the under-delivery is real. Do NOT manufacture gaps to look thorough, invent commitments the user never asked for, or apologize for output you actually shipped. If the audit comes up clean, push back with concrete evidence — never cave to a wrong challenge.

